"Poured from a bottle into a craft beer glass.  It had a hazy brown color that was clear on the bottom half that had a very small head that didn't leave lacing.  It smells of pine and hops with a light nuttiness.  There was a slightly sweet nutty taste up front, with sharp pine taking over in the middle before ending with a slightly bitter hop flavor.  It was certainly a hoppy brown ale as advertised, but it was slightly unbalanced and could've used more nuttiness to balance out the hops.  Medium-light body with moderate carbonation.  It had a pleasant mouthfeel despite the bitter hops aftertaste.  Overall, it is a well hopped brown ale that left room for improvement.  I'm glad I tried it but I didn't like it enough to buy it again."
""
"Ten years ago, I considered Magic Hat a quality craft beer brewer. Today, I consider their brews light weight and boring. I do think that some of their stouts and porters are OK, and some of their limited edition brews worth tasting. This brown ale is OK, but nothing more. I would drink again if another bottle was offered again, but wouldn't buy."
